# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lighthouse-audit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lighthouse-audit/google-lighthouse] Lighthouse [Version 10 - May 2023] includes a metric for Progressive Web Applications to ensure that PWAs are fast, reliable, installable, and optimized for modern mobile technology.
[src:lighthouse-audit/google-lighthouse] Lighthouse can audit webpages in both desktop and mobile versions.
[src:lighthouse-audit/google-lighthouse] In command line mode, developers are able to select specific factors to audit and configure other options using arguments.
[src:lighthouse-audit/google-lighthouse] Recent versions of Lighthouse offer insights into how to optimize the Core Web Vitals metrics, which serve as user experience and performance signals used by Google's search algorithm to rank pages, as announced by Google engineer Addy Osmani in 2021.
[src:lighthouse-audit/google-lighthouse] Lighthouse also calculates **Total Blocking Time (TBT)**, which serves as an excellent lab proxy for evaluating responsiveness issues during page loading.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Lighthouse is an open-source, automated tool to help you improve the quality of web pages.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] You can run it on any web page, public or requiring authentication.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] It has audits for performance, accessibility, SEO, and more.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] You can run Lighthouse in Chrome DevTools, from the command line, or as a Node module.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Give Lighthouse a URL to audit, it runs a series of audits against the page, and then it generates a report on how well the page performed.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Use the failed audits as indicators for how to improve the page.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Each audit has a reference that explains why the audit is important, as well as how to fix it.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] You can also use Lighthouse CI to prevent regressions on your sites.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Lighthouse has its own panel in Chrome DevTools.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Open Chrome, and go to the URL you want to audit.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] DevTools shows you a list of audit categories.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] After 30 to 60 seconds, Lighthouse gives you a report on the page.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Install the current Long-Term Support version of Node.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] The `-g` flag installs it as a global module.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] See Using programmatically for an example of running Lighthouse programmatically, as a Node module.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Install the Lighthouse Chrome Extension from the Chrome Webstore.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Click **Lighthouse**, next to the Chrome address bar or in Chrome's extension menu.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Once clicked, the Lighthouse menu expands.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Lighthouse runs its audits against the currently-focused page, then opens up a new tab with a report of the results.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Use the Lighthouse Viewer to view and share reports online.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] The Lighthouse Viewer needs the JSON output of a Lighthouse report.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Drag the JSON file onto the Viewer, or click anywhere in the Viewer to open your file navigator and select the file.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] If you don't want to manually pass around JSON files, you can also share your reports as secret GitHub gists.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] One benefit of gists is free version control.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] From the Viewer, click more_vert menu, then click **Save as Gist**.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] The first time you do this, a popup asks permission to access your basic GitHub data, and to read and write to your gists.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] To export a report as a gist from the CLI version of Lighthouse, manually create a gist and copy-paste the report's JSON output into the gist.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] The gist filename containing the JSON output must end in `.lighthouse.report.json`.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] See Share reports as JSON for an example of how to generate JSON output from the command line tool.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Lighthouse aims to provide guidance that is relevant and actionable for all web developers.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] To this end, there are two features available that allow you to tailor Lighthouse to your specific needs.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Developers use many different technologies (backend, content management systems, and JavaScript frameworks) to build their web pages.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Instead of surfacing general recommendations, Lighthouse provides relevant and actionable advice, depending on the tools used.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] To contribute a stack pack, review the Contributing Guidelines.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Lighthouse plugins allow domain experts to extend the functionality of Lighthouse for their community's specific needs.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] You can leverage the data that Lighthouse collects to create new audits.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] At its core, a Lighthouse plugin is a node module that implements a set of checks to be run by Lighthouse and added to the report as a new category.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] For more information about how to create your own plugin, check out our Plugin Handbook in the Lighthouse GitHub repo.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] If you're a company or an individual who is integrating Lighthouse as part of the products or services you're offering, that's great!
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] We want as many people as possible to use Lighthouse.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Refer to the Guidelines and Brand Assets for Integrating Lighthouse to show that Lighthouse is used, while protecting our brand.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Lighthouse is open source and contributions are welcome!
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Check out the repository's Issue tracker to find bugs that you can fix, or audits that you can create or improve upon.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] The Issues are a good place to discuss performance metrics, ideas for new audits, or anything else related to Lighthouse.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Except as otherwise noted, the content of this page is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 License, and code samples are licensed under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] For details, see the Google Developers Site Policies.
[src:lighthouse-audit/lighthouse-overview] Java is a registered trademark of Oracle and/or its affiliates.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] Navigation Timing is part of the Performance API and provides metrics associated with navigating from one page to another.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] For example, you can determine how much time it takes to load or unload a document, or log the time it took until DOM construction has finished and interaction with the DOM is possible.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] Only the current document is included, so usually there is only one `PerformanceNavigationTiming` object to observe.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] It extends the `PerformanceEntry` interface with the `entryType` of `"navigation"` and also inherits from `PerformanceResourceTiming`, so all of the timestamps from the process of fetching the document are available as well.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] (Timestamp diagram listing timestamps in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a document) Figure 1.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `unloadEventStart`: (if there is a previous document) the timestamp immediately before the current document's `unload` event handler starts.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `unloadEventEnd`: (if there is a previous document) the timestamp immediately after the current document's `unload` event handler completes.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `domInteractive`: timestamp when DOM construction is finished and interaction with it from JavaScript is possible.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `domContentLoadedEventStart`: timestamp immediately before the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler starts.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `domContentLoadedEventEnd`: timestamp immediately after the current document's `DOMContentLoaded` event handler completes.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `domComplete`: timestamp when the document and all sub-resources have finished loading.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `loadEventStart`: timestamp immediately before the current document's `load` event handler starts.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] `loadEventEnd`: timestamp immediately after the current document's `load` event handler completes.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming.confidence` property returns a `PerformanceTimingConfidence` object containing information that indicates whether a performance record reflects typical application performance, or is likely affected by external factors.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] For example, if a website has loaded after a browser "cold start" or session restore, its pages may load more slowly as a result.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] In such cases, a `low` confidence `value` would be returned for an associated performance record.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] On the other hand, if the browser determines a returned performance record to be representative of typical application performance, a `high` confidence value is returned.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] This confidence measure is useful for developers when trying to determine whether a performance issue is a legitimate concern, or an outlier being caused by external factors.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] See `PerformanceTimingConfidence` for more information.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] The `PerformanceNavigationTiming` interface provides additional properties such as `redirectCount` returning the number of redirects and `type` indicating the type of navigation.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] The `domContentLoadedEventEnd` and `domContentLoadedEventStart` timestamps can be used to measure how long it takes to process the `DOMContentLoaded` event handler.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] This example uses a `PerformanceObserver`, which notifies the caller about new `navigation` performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] The example uses the `buffered` option to access entries that were recorded before the observer was created.
[src:lighthouse-audit/navigation-timing-api] For more examples, see the property pages in the `PerformanceNavigationTiming` reference documentation.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] The **`PerformanceObserver`** interface is used to observe performance measurement events and be notified of new performance entries as they are recorded in the browser's *performance timeline*.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] Creates and returns a new `PerformanceObserver` object.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] Returns an array of the `entryType` values supported by the user agent.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] Specifies the set of entry types to observe.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] The performance observer's callback function will be invoked when performance entry is recorded for one of the specified `entryTypes`.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] Stops the performance observer callback from receiving performance entries.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] Returns the current list of performance entries stored in the performance observer, emptying it out.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] The following example creates a `PerformanceObserver` watching for "mark" (`PerformanceMark`) and "measure" (`PerformanceMeasure`) events.
[src:lighthouse-audit/performanceobserver] The `perfObserver` callback provides a `list` (`PerformanceObserverEntryList`) which allows you to get observed performance entries.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] Resource Timing is part of the Performance API and enables retrieving and analyzing detailed network timing data for the loading of an application's resources.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] An application can use the timing metrics to determine, for example, the length of time it takes to load a specific resource (such as an image or a script) either implicitly as part of page load or explicitly from JavaScript, for example using the `fetch()` API.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] Every resource on a document will be represented by a `PerformanceResourceTiming` entry (extending the `PerformanceEntry` interface) with the `entryType` of `"resource"`.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] For each `PerformanceResourceTiming` entry, a *resource loading timeline* will be recorded, with high-resolution timestamps for network events such as redirect start and end times, DNS lookup start and end times, request start, response start and end times, and so on.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] Besides the timestamps, other properties that provide information about the resource are included as well, such the size of the fetched resource, or the type of resource that initiated the fetch.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] See Typical resource timing metrics in the reference page for the `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] (Timestamp diagram listing timestamps in the order in which they are recorded for the fetching of a resource) Figure 1.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] An application can get timestamps for the various stages used to load a resource.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] For example the `startTime`, DNS timestamps, connection set up times and then various resource download times.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] See timestamps in the reference page for the `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] The `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface has three properties that can be used to obtain size data about a resource.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] The `transferSize` property returns the size (in bytes) of the fetched resource including the response header fields plus the response payload body.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] The `encodedBodySize` property returns the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache), of the *payload body*, **before** removing any applied content-codings.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] `decodedBodySize` returns the size (in octets) received from the fetch (HTTP or cache) of the *message body*, **after** removing any applied content-codings.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] The `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface provides additional resources information.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] Consult the reference docs for the full list of properties.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] If your website or application fetches more than 250 resources and you want to record more than 250 `PerformanceResourceTiming` entries, you need to increase the size of the resource timing buffer.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] To set the size of the browser's performance resource data buffer, use the `Performance.setResourceTimingBufferSize()` method, and to clear the browser's performance resource data buffer, use the `Performance.clearResourceTimings()` method.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] To get notified when the browser's resource timing buffer is full, listen for the `resourcetimingbufferfull` event.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] The following call allows 500 `"resource"` performance entries in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] For more information, see also Managing buffer sizes.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] Many of the resource timing properties are restricted to return `0` or an empty string when the resource is a cross-origin request.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] To expose cross-origin timing information, the `Timing-Allow-Origin` HTTP response header needs to be set.
[src:lighthouse-audit/resource-timing-api] For more information on the fields affected, see Cross-origin timing information in the reference page for the `PerformanceResourceTiming` interface.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] User Timing is part of the Performance API and allows you to measure the performance of applications using high-precision timestamps that are part of the browser's performance timeline.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The browser provides certain information (called *performance entries*) to the browser's performance timeline for you.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] This includes, for example, entries provided by the Resource Timing API that determine the time it takes to fetch a resource like an image.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The browser, however, can not determine what is going on in your application.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] For example, when a user clicks a button or performs a specific task within your application, there is no high-precision performance measurement.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The User Timing API is an extension to the browser's performance timeline and helps you to measure and record performance data that is custom to your application.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The advantage of using this API, over calls to `Date.now()` or `performance.now()`, is that you can give the markers a name and that it integrates well with performance tooling.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] Browser's developer tools can display performance marks in Performance Panels, and it also works with other performance APIs like `PerformanceObserver` objects.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] As a first step to start measuring the performance of your app's functionality, you need to add named performance markers at important places in your code.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] Ideally, you go through your codebase and determine critical paths and important tasks for which you want to ensure they can be performed fast.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The `performance.mark()` method is used to create a `PerformanceMark`.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The method takes one argument, the `name` of the mark, as shown in the following example.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] If the `name` argument isn't enough, `mark()` is configurable using an options object where you can put additional information in the `detail` property, which can be of any type.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] You can also set a different `startTime` if needed.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] In the following code, the `startTime` is set to `12.5`, and additional information, like the HTML element used, is provided with `detail`.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] Now that you added markers to your application, you can measure the time between them.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The `Performance.measure()` method is used to create a `PerformanceMeasure` object.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] It accepts a `name` parameter, used to identify the measure, and two marks, `start` and `end`, that it should measure between.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The following example creates a `"login-duration"` measure and measures between the start and the finish of the login process.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The object then has a `duration` property which calculates the end mark timestamp minus the start mark timestamp for you.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] For example, you can log this value or send it to some analytics endpoint.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The `Performance.measure()` method is also configurable using an options object, so you can do more advanced measurements or provide additional information using the `detail` property.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] For example, you can use the `event.timestamp` property from a `click` event to know exactly when a user clicked login and measure that to the point in time when the UI was updated, which is the `"login-finished"` marker here.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The preferred way to get notified about your custom performance measures is the use of `PerformanceObserver` objects.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] Performance observers allow you to subscribe passively to performance marks and measures as they happen.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] For more information, see `PerformanceObserver`.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] There are many different performance entries in the browser's performance timeline.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] Some are added by the browser, and some might be added by you, like the login markers and measures from the examples above.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] To retrieve performance marks and measures at a single point in time, the `Performance` interface provides three methods, as shown below.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The `performance.getEntries()` method gets all performance entries.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The `performance.getEntriesByType(entryType)` method filters the entries by type already.
[src:lighthouse-audit/user-timing-api] The `performance.getEntriesByName(name, entryType)` method allows you to get specific marks or measures by name.
